<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<head>
<title>@HI{{you to @KJ{{think}}u}}</title>
<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="japanese.css"/>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
</head>

<body>

<h1>@HI{{you to @KJ{{think}}u}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vyou{{}}@HI{{to @KJ{{think}}u}}
<li> @Vyou{{}}@HI{{to @KJ{{think}}tteiru}}
<li> @Vru{{}}@HI{{mai to @KJ{{think}}u}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
A sentence ending in the plain volitional followed by @HI{{to @KJ{{think}}u}} indicates something that the speaker wishes to do.
@HI{{to @KJ{{think}}tteiru}} expresses a similar meaning except it implies that the decision was made some time ago.
</p>

<p>
The negative form is @Vru{{}}@HI{{mai to @KJ{{think}}u}}.
</p>

<p>
The verb before @HI{{to@KJ{{think}}u}} must be something controllable by human volition.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{summer^rest}}mini @KJ{{day^book}}@KT{{arupusu}}ni@KJ{{ascend}}rou to@KJ{{think}}imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I think I will climb the Japanese Alps during the summer holiday.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{week^end}}ha @KJ{{sea}}ni @KJ{{going}}kou to @KJ{{think}}tte imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'm thinking of going to the beach at the weekend.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{now}}kara @KJ{{silver^going}}he @KJ{{going}}kou to @KJ{{think}}imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'm going to the bank.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{me}}ha ano@KJ{{person}}to ha mou @KJ{{tale}}sumai to@KJ{{think}}u.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I think I won't talk to that person any more.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When the subject is not the speaker, this sentence pattern cannot be used. This is because @HI{{to @KJ{{think}}u}}
refers only to the speaker's thoughts.
Under these circumstances use @HI{{@KJ{{think}}tte iru}} to indicate that the subject "has indicated that he feels".
</p>

